"Things don’t always go as planned, even in programs. Maybe
a file doesn’t exist, someone enters the wrong type of input,
or a program tries to divide by zero. In C++, we use
exception handling to deal with these unexpected problems.
• For this activity, explain the idea behind exception handling
and why it’s important. Think of a real-life situation where
something goes wrong, and you need a backup plan. For
example, what happens if your GPS loses signal, or if a
vending machine runs out of snacks after you’ve paid?
• Try to relate that idea to how programs need to handle
errors gracefully instead of crashing."

Response:
Exception handling is a way to develop program contingency plans. Certain input, for example, 
will alter the output in ways that are unexpected, such as inputting an integer when prompted
for a name string input. Exception handlign "gracefully" responds with an error message, 
instead of breaking the entire program, so that any input previously haandled is not lost in 
a program reset. To make a real world example, if I were in a conversation with someone, and they
said soemthing that absolutely bewildered me, and I couldn't respond to it, I would respectfully explain
that I do not understand, or that there was an issue with what they said, and give them the opportunity to
 rephrase, rather than ending the conversation or trying to go back to the beginning.